## Phase 3.3 – Health Endpoint

### Change Introduced
A dedicated `/health` endpoint was introduced to expose application health status.

This endpoint allows external systems to verify whether the application is healthy and responsive.

---

### Detection
- Detected by: Manual testing via browser
- Detection point: HTTP response from `/health`
- Signal: 200 OK response with body "OK"

---

### Time Metrics
- Time to implement: ~10 minutes
- Time to verify: ~5 minutes

---

### Root Cause
Previously, there was no way to programmatically determine application health.

The system relied solely on process existence and manual observation.

This made automated health verification impossible.

---

### Fix Applied
A `/health` route was added inside the request handler.

The endpoint:
- Returns HTTP 200 when healthy
- Does not increment request metrics
- Logs health check activity

Health traffic is separated from normal user traffic.

---

### Prevention / Optimization
- Always expose a health endpoint in production services
- Separate health probes from user request metrics
- Ensure health checks are lightweight and fast

---

### Outcome
The application now provides:

- Structured logs (Phase 3.1)
- Runtime metrics (Phase 3.2)
- A health verification endpoint (Phase 3.3)

The service is now monitorable by infrastructure systems such as load balancers and orchestrators.

