## Phase 3.4 – Degradation Awareness (Uptime & Load Threshold)

### Change Introduced
Basic degradation detection was introduced into the application.

The system now:
- Tracks application uptime
- Detects high request volume
- Emits warning logs when request thresholds are exceeded
- Returns uptime information via the `/health` endpoint

---

### Detection
- Detected by: Manual testing during local runtime
- Detection point: Console log output and `/health` endpoint
- Signal:
  - Uptime value increases over time
  - Warning logs appear when request count exceeds threshold

---

### Time Metrics
- Time to implement: ~15 minutes
- Time to verify: ~10 minutes

---

### Root Cause
Previously, the system could only report whether it was alive.

There was no awareness of:
- How long it had been running
- Whether traffic load was increasing
- When behavior was crossing normal boundaries

This limited operational insight into performance trends.

---

### Fix Applied
The application was enhanced to:

- Track start time at boot
- Calculate uptime dynamically
- Introduce a request threshold warning
- Emit WARNING-level logs when traffic exceeds defined limits

The `/health` endpoint now includes uptime information.

---

### Prevention / Optimization
- Monitor trends, not just binary status
- Emit early warning signals before failure
- Track uptime to understand lifecycle behavior
- Detect degradation before system crash

---

### Outcome
The system now provides:

- Structured logs (Phase 3.1)
- Runtime metrics (Phase 3.2)
- Health endpoint (Phase 3.3)
- Degradation awareness via uptime and load signals (Phase 3.4)

The application can now distinguish between healthy, busy, and potentially degrading states.